sbol:Collection.dcterms:title: iGEM Parts Registry
sbol:Collection.dcterms:description: The iGEM Registry is a growing collection of genetic parts that can be mixed and matched to build synthetic biology devices and systems. As part of the synthetic biology community's efforts to make biology easier to engineer, it provides a source of genetic parts to iGEM teams and academic labs.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K364310
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: The ecdysone receptor is a nuclear receptor found in arthropods, where it controls development and contributes to other processes such as reproduction. The receptor is a non-covalent heterodimer of two proteins, the EcR protein and ultraspiracle protein (USP). It binds to and is activated by ecdysteroids. Pulses of 20-hydroxyecdysone occur during insect development, whereupon this hormone binds to the ecdysone receptor, a ligand-activated transcription factor found in the nuclei of insect cells. This in turn leads to the activation of many other genes,WHICH Ultimately causes physiological changes that result in ecdysis (moulting).
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Lior Malka
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: Human EcR (of the nuclear hormone receptor superfamily)
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: The reconstruction of the DBD to the hinge region, LBD and Backbone will be done with RFC 25
